<section xml:id="C24.S17">
<title>Mathematical Applications</title>        
   
<subsection xml:id="C24.S17.SS1">
<title>Summation</title>        
 
<paragraph xml:id="C24.S17.Px1">
<title>Euler–Maclaurin Summation Formula</title>  
   
<para xml:id="C24.S17.Px1.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C24.S17.Px1.p1.s1">
See §2.10(i).
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C24.S17.Px1.p1.s2">
For a generalization seeOlver (1997b, p. 284).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</paragraph>
 
<paragraph xml:id="C24.S17.Px2">
<title>Boole Summation Formula</title>  
   
<para xml:id="C24.S17.Px2.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C24.S17.Px2.p1.s1">
Let <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px2.p1.m1">0\leq h\leq 1</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px2.p1.m2">a,m</Math> , and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px2.p1.m3">n</Math> be integers such that <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px2.p1.m4">n&gt;a</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px2.p1.m5">m&gt;0</Math> , and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px2.p1.m6">f^{(m)}(x)</Math> is absolutely integrable over <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px2.p1.m7">[a,n]</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C24.S17.Px2.p1.s2">
Then with the notation of § 24.2(iii)
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="5" xml:id="C24.S17.Px2.p1.s3">
<Math equation-number="24.17.1" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S17.E1">\sum_{j=a}^{n-1}(-1)^{j}f(j+h)=\frac{1}{2}\sum_{k=0}^{m-1}\frac{E_{k}\left(h \right)}{k!}\left((-1)^{n-1}f^{(k)}(n)+(-1)^{a}f^{(k)}(a)\right)+R_{m}(n)</Math> , where <Math equation-number="24.17.2" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S17.E2">R_{m}(n)=\frac{1}{2(m-1)!}\int_{a}^{n}f^{(m)}(x)\widetilde{E}_{m-1}\left(h-x \right)\mathrm{d}x</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</paragraph>
 
<paragraph xml:id="C24.S17.Px3">
