</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C24.S17.SS2">
<title>Spline Functions</title>        
 
<paragraph xml:id="C24.S17.Px4">
<title>Euler Splines</title>  
  
<para xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="8" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.s1">
Let <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.m1">\mathcal{S}_{n}</Math> denote the class of functions that have <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.m2">n-1</Math> continuous derivatives on <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.m3">\mathbb{R}</Math> and are polynomials of degree at most <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.m4">n</Math> in each interval <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.m5">(k,k+1)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.m6">k\in\mathbb{Z}</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="9" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.s2">
The members of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.m7">\mathcal{S}_{n}</Math> are calledcardinal spline functions.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="10" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.s3">
The functions <Math equation-number="24.17.3" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S17.E3">S_{n}(x)=\frac{\widetilde{E}_{n}\left(x+\tfrac{1}{2}n+\tfrac{1}{2}\right)}{ \widetilde{E}_{n}\left(\tfrac{1}{2}n+\tfrac{1}{2}\right)}, if n=0,1,\dots,</Math> are called Euler splines of degree <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.m8">n</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="4" sentence-num-in-section="11" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.s4">
For each <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.m9">n</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.m10">S_{n}(x)</Math> is the unique bounded function such that <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.m11">S_{n}(x)\in\mathcal{S}_{n}</Math> and <Math equation-number="24.17.4" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S17.E4">S_{n}(k)=(-1)^{k}, if k\in\mathbb{Z}</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="5" sentence-num-in-section="12" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.s5">
The function <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px4.p1.m12">S_{n}(x)</Math> is also optimal in a certain sense; seeSchoenberg (1971).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</paragraph>
 
<paragraph xml:id="C24.S17.Px5">
<title>Bernoulli Monosplines</title>  
     
 
<para xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="13" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p1.s1">
A function of the form <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p1.m1">x^{n}-S(x)</Math> , with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p1.m2">S(x)\in\mathcal{S}_{n-1}</Math> is called a cardinal monospline of degree <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p1.m3">n</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="14" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p1.s2">
Again with the notation of §24.2(iii) define <Math equation-number="24.17.5" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S17.E5">M_{n}(x)=\begin{cases}\widetilde{B}_{n}\left(x\right)-B_{n},&amp;n\text{ even},\\ \widetilde{B}_{n}\left(x+\frac{1}{2}\right),&amp;n\text{ odd}.\end{cases</Math> } <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p1.m4">M_{n}(x)</Math> is a monospline of degree <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p1.m5">n</Math> , and it follows from (24.4.25) and (24.4.27) that <Math equation-number="24.17.6" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S17.E6">M_{n}(k)=0, if k\in\mathbb{Z}</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="15" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p1.s3">
For each <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p1.m6">n=1,2,\dots</Math> the function <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p1.m7">M_{n}(x)</Math> is also the unique cardinal monospline of degree <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p1.m8">n</Math> satisfying (24.17.6), provided that <Math equation-number="24.17.7" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S17.E7">M_{n}(x)=O\left(|x|^{\gamma}\right), if x\to\pm\infty,</Math> for some positive constant <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p1.m9">\gamma</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="16" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p2.s1">
For any <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p2.m1">n\geq 2</Math> the function <Math equation-number="24.17.8" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S17.E8">F(x)=\widetilde{B}_{n}\left(x\right)-2^{-n}B_{n}</Math> is the unique cardinal monospline of degree <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p2.m2">n</Math> having the least supremum norm <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p2.m3">\|F\|_{\infty}</Math> on <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.Px5.p2.m4">\mathbb{R}</Math> (minimality property).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</paragraph>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C24.S17.SS3">
<title>Number Theory</title>        
    
 
<para xml:id="C24.S17.SS3.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="17" xml:id="C24.S17.SS3.p1.s1">
Bernoulli and Euler numbers and polynomials occur in: number theory via (24.4.7), (24.4.8), and other identities involving sums of powers; the Riemann zeta function and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.SS3.p1.m1">L</Math> -series (§25.15,Apostol(1976), and Ireland and Rosen (1990)); arithmetic of cyclotomic fields and the classical theory of Fermat’s last theorem (Ribenboim (1979) and Washington (1997)); <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S17.SS3.p1.m2">p</Math> -adic analysis (Koblitz (1984, Chapter 2)).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
